{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639088"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17763"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17763"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.05,0.07,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72382"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57852"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24522"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72382"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a history of chronic heartburn and regurgitation for the past five years. He has a medical history of gastroesophageal reflux disease and takes proton pump inhibitors intermittently. He does not smoke or drink alcohol. An upper endoscopy performed recently revealed changes consistent with Barrett\u0027s oesophagus (Image). Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is a risk factor for certain conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely complication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenocarcinoma","Gastric carcinoma","Oesophageal stricture","Peptic ulcer disease","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is a condition where the normal squamous epithelium lining the oesophagus is replaced by columnar epithelium, a process known as intestinal metaplasia. This change is typically due to chronic gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. The significance of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus lies in its potential to progress to oesophageal adenocarcinoma, a type of cancer. The annual risk of oesophageal adenocarcinoma in patients with documented Barrett\u0027s is \u0026lt;0.2%. However, that risk is sufficient to justify regular surveillance of these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely progression of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus if left untreated. The risk of progression to adenocarcinoma is higher in patients with dysplasia, which is why regular surveillance and management are recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is another type of oesophageal cancer, but it is not associated with Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. It is more commonly linked to smoking and alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E refers to cancer of the stomach, which is not directly related to Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. While both conditions involve the gastrointestinal tract, they have different risk factors and pathophysiology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal stricture\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential complication of chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease but is not a progression of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. It results from scarring and narrowing of the oesophagus due to repeated injury from acid reflux.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic ulcer disease\u003C/strong\u003E involves ulceration of the stomach or duodenal lining and is not related to Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. It is typically caused by Helicobacter pylori infection or nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is a condition where the normal squamous epithelium of the oesophagus is replaced by columnar epithelium due to chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease.","Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is a known risk factor for the development of oesophageal adenocarcinoma.","Regular surveillance and management of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus can help reduce the risk of progression to adenocarcinoma."],"references":["Gregson EM, Bornschein J, Fitzgerald RC. Genetic progression of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus to oesophageal adenocarcinoma. Br J Cancer. 2016 Aug 9;115(4):403-10. doi: 10.1038/bjc.2016.219. Epub 2016 Jul 21. PMID: 27441494; PMCID: PMC4985359.","Zhang HY, Spechler SJ, Souza RF. Esophageal adenocarcinoma arising in Barrett esophagus. Cancer Lett. 2009 Mar 18;275(2):170-7. doi: 10.1016/j.canlet.2008.07.006. Epub 2008 Aug 13. PMID: 18703277; PMCID: PMC2673195.","Wijnhoven BP, Tilanus HW, Dinjens WN. Molecular biology of Barrett\u0027s adenocarcinoma. Ann Surg. 2001 Mar;233(3):322-37. doi: 10.1097/00000658-200103000-00005. PMID: 11224619; PMCID: PMC1421247.","Hvid-Jensen F, Pedersen L, Drewes AM, S\u00f8rensen HT, Funch-Jensen P. Incidence of adenocarcinoma among patients with Barrett\u0027s esophagus. N Engl J Med. 2011 Oct 13;365(15):1375-83. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa1103042. PMID: 21995385."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17763"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21351"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type"